[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Canonical Ltd. has created and continues to back several projects.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Principally these are free and open-source software (FOSS) or tools designed to improve collaboration between free software developers and contributors.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Some projects require a Contributor License Agreement to be signed.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In 2007, Canonical launched an International online shop selling support services and Ubuntu-branded goods; later in 2008 it expanded that with a United States-specific shop designed to reduce shipment times.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] At the same time, the word *Ubuntu* was trademarked in connection with clothing and accessories.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In a *Guardian* interview in May 2008, Shuttleworth said that Canonical's business model was service provision and that Canonical was not yet close to profitability.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Canonical stated that it would wait three to five years to become profitable.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Shuttleworth regarded Canonical as positioning itself as demand for services related to free software rose.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] This strategy has been compared to Red Hat's business strategies in the 1990s.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In an early-2009 *New York Times* article, Shuttleworth said that Canonical's revenue was "creeping" towards US$30 million, the company's break-even point.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Canonical achieved a small operating profit of $281,000 in 2009, but until 2017 struggled to maintain financial solvency and took a major financial hit from the development of Unity and Ubuntu Touch, leading to an operating loss of $21.6 million for the fiscal year 2013.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] The company reported an operating profit of $2 million in 2017 after shutting down the Unity development team and laying off nearly 200 employees.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] The company now plans to focus on its server and professional support products and services, which have proved to be most profitable.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Through this, Canonical plans to maintain solvency and achieve long-term profitability.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In 2022, Canonical UK Limited (a subsidiary of the group) made a profit of £0.52m on revenues of £14.31m.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Canonical reported a revenue of $175M in 2021.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In 2023, the company reported a revenue of $251M.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] The head office is in London on the 5th Floor of 3 More London Riverside, More London.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Previous office locations include the 5th Floor of the Blue Fin Building, Southwark Street, and the 27th floor of Millbank Tower.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] In the summer of 2006, Canonical opened an office in Montreal to house its global support and services operation.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] Taipei 101 is also home to a Canonical office.
[src:snap-packages/canonical-company] There was formerly an OEM team in Lexington, Massachusetts, United States.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:snap-packages/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:snap-packages/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Applications in a Snap run in a container with limited access to the host system.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Using *Interfaces*, users can give an application mediated access to additional features of the host such as recording audio, accessing USB devices and recording video.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] These interfaces mediate regular Linux APIs so that applications can function in the sandbox without needing to be rewritten.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Desktop applications can also use the XDG Desktop Portals, a standardized API originally created by the Flatpak project (originally called xdg-app) to give sandboxed desktop applications access to host resources.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] These portals often provide a better user experience compared to the native Linux APIs because they prompt the user for permission to use resources such as a webcam at the time the application uses them.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The downside is that applications and toolkits need to be rewritten in order to use these newer APIs.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The Snap sandbox also supports sharing data and Unix sockets between Snaps.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] This is often used to share common libraries and application frameworks between Snaps to reduce the size of Snaps by avoiding duplication.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The Snap sandbox heavily relies on the AppArmor Linux Security Module from the upstream Linux kernel.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Because only one "major" Linux Security Module (LSM) can be active at the same time, the Snap sandbox is much less secure when another major LSM is enabled.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] As a result, on distributions such as Fedora which enable SELinux by default, the Snap sandbox is heavily degraded.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Although Canonical is working with many other developers and companies to make it possible for multiple LSMs to run at the same time, in 2020 this solution was still a long time away.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Multiple times a day, snapd checks for available updates of all Snaps and installs them in the background using an atomic operation.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Updates can be reverted and use delta encoding to reduce their download size.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Publishers can release and update multiple versions of their software in parallel using *channels*.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Each channel has a specific *track* and *risk*, which indicate the *version* and *stability* of the software released on that channel.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] When installing an application, Snap defaults to using the `latest/stable` channel, which will automatically update to new major releases of the software when they become available.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Publishers can create additional channels to give users the possibility to stick to specific major releases of their software.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] For example, a `2.0/stable` channel would allow users to stick to the 2.0 version of the software and only get minor updates without the risk of backwards incompatible changes.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] When the publisher releases a new major version in a new channel, users can manually update to the next version when they choose.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The schedule, frequency and timing of automatic updates can be configured by users.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Users can also pause automatic updates for a certain period of time, or indefinitely.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Updates are automatically paused on metered connections.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snapcraft is a tool for developers to package their programs in the Snap format.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] It runs on any Linux distribution supported by Snap, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snapcraft builds the packages in a Virtual Machine using Multipass, in order to ensure the result of a build is the same, regardless of which distribution or operating system it is built on.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snapcraft supports multiple build tools and programming languages, such as Go, Java, JavaScript, Python, C/C++ and Rust.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] It also allows importing application metadata from multiple sources such as AppStream, git, shell scripts and `setup.py` files.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The Snap Store allows developers to publish their snap-packaged applications.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] All apps uploaded to the Snap Store undergo automatic testing, including a malware scan.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] However, the scan does not catch all issues.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] In one case in May 2018, two applications by the same developer were found to contain a cryptocurrency miner which ran in the background during application execution.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] In 2024, fake cryptocurrency wallets were uploaded that would steal the user's funds, and then when taken down by Canonical, simply reuploaded by a new account.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Canonical recommends users only install Snaps from publishers trusted by the user.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The snap file format is a single compressed filesystem using the SquashFS format with the extension `.snap`.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] This filesystem contains the application, libraries it depends on, and declarative metadata.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] This metadata is interpreted by snapd to set up an appropriately shaped secure sandbox for that application.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] After installation, the snap is mounted by the host operating system and decompressed on the fly when the files are used.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Although this has the advantage that snaps use less disk space, it also means some large applications start more slowly.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snap supports any class of Linux application such as desktop applications, server tools, IoT apps and even system services such as the printer driver stack.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] To ensure this, Snap relies on systemd for features such as running socket-activated system services in a Snap.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] This causes Snap to work best only on distributions that can adopt that init system.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snap initially only supported the all-Snap Ubuntu Core distribution, but in June 2016, it was ported to a wide range of Linux distributions to become a format for universal Linux packages.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snap requires Systemd which is available in most, but not all, Linux distributions.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] ChromeOS does not support Snap directly, only through Linux distributions installed in it that support Snap, such as Gallium OS.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Ubuntu and its official derivatives pre-install Snap by default, as well as other Ubuntu-based distributions such as KDE Neon, and Zorin OS.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Solus have currently planned to drop Snap, to reduce the burden of maintaining AppArmor patches needed for strict Snap confinement.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Zorin OS have removed Snap as a default package in the Zorin OS 17 release.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] While other official Ubuntu derivatives such as Kubuntu, Xubuntu, and Ubuntu MATE have also shipped with the competing Flatpak as a complement, they will no longer do so beginning with Ubuntu 23.04, meaning that it must be installed manually by the user.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] A number of notable desktop software development companies publish their software in the Snap Store, including Google, JetBrains, KDE, Microsoft (for Linux versions of e.g. .NET Core 3.1, Visual Studio Code, Skype, and PowerShell), Mozilla and Spotify.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Snaps are also used in Internet-of-Things environments, ranging from consumer-facing products to enterprise device management gateways and satellite communication networks.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Finally, Snap is also used by developers of server applications such as InfluxDB, Kata Containers, Nextcloud and Travis CI.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] Clément Lefèbvre, founder and project leader of Linux Mint, criticized Snap, arguing that Canonical controls the distribution of software and makes its store a requirement for Snap users.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] In 2020, the Linux Mint project announced that its releases would not ship with snap software and would not allow snap packages to be installed automatically via APT.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] On recent versions of Ubuntu, Canonical has migrated certain packages exclusively to Snap, such as Chromium and Firefox web browsers.
[src:snap-packages/snap-software] The replacement of Firefox led to mixed reception from users due to performance issues with the Snap version, especially on startup.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:snap-packages/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu is published on a six-month release cycle, with long-term support (LTS) versions issued every two years.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Canonical provides security updates and support until each release reaches its designated end-of-life (EOL), with optional extended support available through the Ubuntu Pro and Expanded Security Maintenance (ESM) services.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu can be installed directly on hardware or run within a virtual machine.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It is widely used for cloud computing, with integration support for platforms such as OpenStack.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It is also one of the most popular Linux distributions for general desktop use, supported by extensive online communities such as Ask Ubuntu, and has spawned numerous community-maintained variants.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The name "Ubuntu" comes from the Nguni philosophy of **ubuntu**, which translates roughly as "humanity to others" or "I am what I am because of who we all are".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In April 2004, Mark Shuttleworth invited a dozen Debian developers to his London flat, where they brainstormed and laid out the distinguishing features of what would become Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Shuttleworth chose the "Ubuntu" name for his South African roots and to emphasize community.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] To fund the project, Shuttleworth created Canonical Ltd. to employ the developers using his fortune from selling Thawte to Verisign.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For the first year, the company had no physical offices and employees used online platforms to coordinate, fostering transparency.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The group set a six-month deadline and decided only to announce Ubuntu during its first release—October 2004: "Warty Warthog".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] On 8 July 2005, Shuttleworth and Canonical launched the newly-created Ubuntu Foundation and provided initial funding of US$10 million.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The purpose of the foundation is to ensure the support and development for all future versions of Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Mark Shuttleworth described the foundation's goal as to ensure the continuity of the Ubuntu project.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] On 12 March 2009, Ubuntu announced developer support for third-party cloud management platforms, such as those used at Amazon EC2.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2011, Ubuntu's default desktop was changed from GNOME 2 to the in-house Unity instead of GNOME 3.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2014, Canonical announced Snappy Ubuntu Core, an immutable OS designed for use in embedded systems, along with its new package manager named "Snappy" derived from the Ubuntu Phone project.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] By the release of Ubuntu 16.04, the package management system was renamed "Snap" and supported desktop apps, becoming an alternative to Flatpak.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] After nearly 6.5 years, the default desktop was changed back to GNOME 3 in 2017, upon the release of version 17.10.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu, since version 16.04.5, requires a 2 GB or larger installation medium.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The last release of Ubuntu available on a minimal CD was 18.04.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] 32-bit x86 processors were supported up to Ubuntu 18.04.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It was decided to support "legacy software", i.e. select 32-bit i386 packages, for Ubuntu 19.10 (since out of support) and 20.04 LTS.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2022, Ubuntu consolidated its extended security maintenance and hardening services into the Ubuntu Pro subscriptions, including LivePatch, a feature that allows devices to perform select security updates without reboots, available free-of-charge for personal use on up to five machines.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In June 2023, Canonical announced Ubuntu Core Desktop, an immutable desktop OS, completely made of snap packages like Ubuntu Core and slated for release along Ubuntu 24.04 LTS.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Its release was indefinitely delayed, as the vision for major advantages had not yet been fully realized.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] After a rise in the popularity of cryptocurrency scam packages, the Snap Store started requiring manual approval for new applications in March 2024.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] On 9 August 2024, Ubuntu announced a change in policy to always use the latest upstream version of the Linux kernel at the time of each Ubuntu release, even if the kernel code has not seen a stable release and is still in release candidate status.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Support for the X11 windowing system was dropped in favour of the alternative Wayland with Ubuntu version 25.10 in 2025, which shipped with GNOME 49 which had made the change.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu is built on Debian's architecture and infrastructure, and comprises Linux server, desktop, and discontinued phone and tablet operating system versions.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As of version 24.10, a default installation of Ubuntu contains a minimal selection of software, namely a web browser (Firefox), and basic GNOME utilities (including the desktop).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Many additional software packages are accessible from the built-in Ubuntu Software (previously Ubuntu Software Center), as well as any other APT-based package management tools.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Many additional software packages that are no longer installed by default, such as Evolution, GIMP, Pidgin, and Synaptic, are still accessible in the repositories and installable by the main tool or by any other APT-based package management tool.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Cross-distribution snap packages and Flatpaks are also available, that both allow installing software, such as some of Microsoft's software, in most of the major Linux operating systems (such as any currently supported Ubuntu version and in Fedora).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The default file manager is GNOME Files, formerly called Nautilus.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] All of the application software installed by default is free software.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In addition, Ubuntu redistributes some hardware drivers that are available only in binary format, but such packages are clearly marked in the restricted component.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Current long-term support (LTS) releases are supported for five years, and are released every two years.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Since the release of Ubuntu 6.06, every fourth release receives long-term support.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Long-term support includes updates for new hardware, security patches, and updates to the 'Ubuntu stack' (cloud computing infrastructure).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The first LTS releases were supported for three years on the desktop and five years on the server; since Ubuntu 12.04 LTS, desktop support for LTS releases was increased to five years as well.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] LTS releases get regular point releases with support for new hardware and integration of all the updates published in that series to date.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu packages are based on Debian's unstable branch, which are synchronized every six months.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Both distributions use Debian's package management tools (e.g.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] APT and GNOME Software) and deb format of packages.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Debian and Ubuntu packages are not necessarily binary compatible with each other, however, some packages may need to be rebuilt from source to be used in Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Many Ubuntu developers are also maintainers of key packages within Debian.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu cooperates with Debian by pushing changes back to Debian, although there has been criticism that this does not happen often enough.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ian Murdock, the founder of Debian, had expressed concern about Ubuntu packages potentially diverging too far from Debian to remain compatible.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Before release, packages are imported from Debian unstable continuously and merged with Ubuntu-specific modifications.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] At some point during the release process, the Debian Import Freeze is implemented.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] This prevents the automatic import of packages from Debian without an explicit request from a developer.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In combination with other freezes, this helps packagers ensure that frozen features interoperate well together.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] All official Ubuntu packages are available from hundreds of mirrors worldwide.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As of 30 March 2025, there were a total of 617 Ubuntu mirrors operating.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] User programs run with low privileges and cannot corrupt the operating system or other users' files.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For increased security, the sudo tool is used to assign temporary privileges for performing administrative tasks, which allows the root account to remain locked and helps prevent inexperienced users from inadvertently making catastrophic system changes or opening security holes.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Polkit is also being widely implemented into the desktop.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Most network ports are closed by default to prevent hacking.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] A built-in firewall, Uncomplicated Firewall, allows end-users who install network servers to control access.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu compiles its packages using GCC features such as PIE and buffer overflow protection to harden its software.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] These extra features greatly increase security at the performance expense of 0.01% in 64-bit.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu also supports full disk encryption, as well as encryption of the home and private directories.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The system requirements vary among Ubuntu products.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For the Ubuntu desktop release 22.04 LTS (and still for 24.04.3), a PC with at least 2 GHz dual-core processor, 4 GB of RAM and 25 GB of free disk space is recommended.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For less powerful computers, there are other Ubuntu distributions such as Lubuntu and Xubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu also supports the ARM architecture.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It is also available on Power ISA, while older PowerPC architecture was at one point unofficially supported, and now newer Power ISA CPUs (POWER8) are supported.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The x86-64 ("AMD64") architecture is also officially supported.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Live images are the typical way for users to assess and subsequently install Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] These can be downloaded as a disk image (.iso) and subsequently burnt to a DVD or USB flash drive and then booted.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Other methods include running the live version via Ventoy, UNetbootin, Universal USB Installer, or Startup Disk Creator (a pre-installed tool on Ubuntu, available on machines already running the OS) directly from a USB drive (making, respectively, a live DVD or live USB medium).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Running Ubuntu in this way is slower than running it from a hard drive, but does not alter the computer unless specifically instructed by the user.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] If the user chooses to boot the live image rather than execute an installer at boot time, there is still the option to then use the Ubuntu Desktop Installer once booted into the live environment.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The Ubuntu Desktop Installer replaced the former Ubiquity installer since Ubuntu 23.04.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Disk images of all current and past versions are available for download at the Ubuntu web site.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Additionally, USB flash drive installations can be used to boot Ubuntu and Kubuntu in a way that allows permanent saving of user settings and portability of the USB-installed system between physical machines (however, the computers' BIOS must support booting from USB).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In newer versions of Ubuntu, the Ubuntu Live USB creator can be used to install Ubuntu on a USB drive (with or without a live CD or DVD).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Creating a bootable USB drive with persistence is as simple as dragging a slider to determine how much space to reserve for persistence; for this, Ubuntu employs casper.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu divides most software into four domains to reflect differences in licensing and the degree of support available.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Some unsupported applications receive updates from community members known as "Masters of the Universe" (MOTU).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Before January 2023, community supported free software in *Universe* repository received no updates at all from Canonical Ltd.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Since 26 January 2023, customers of the Ubuntu Pro subscription service—which is free for personal use—can get Canonical-supported updates also for packages in *Universe* repository.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Free software includes software that has met the Ubuntu licensing requirements, which roughly correspond to the Debian Free Software Guidelines.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Exceptions, however, include firmware, in the Main category, because although some firmware is not allowed to be modified, its distribution is still permitted.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Non-free software is usually unsupported (Multiverse), but some exceptions (Restricted) are made for important non-free software and/or software potentially illegal in some territories.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Supported non-free software includes device drivers that can be used to run Ubuntu on some current hardware, such as binary-only graphics card drivers.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The level of support in the Restricted category is more limited than that of Main, because the developers may not have access to the source code.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It is intended that Main and Restricted should contain all software needed for a complete desktop environment.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In addition to the above, in which the software does not receive new features after an initial release, *Ubuntu Backports* is an officially recognised repository for backporting newer software from later versions of Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The *-updates* repository provides stable release updates (SRU) of Ubuntu and are generally installed through update-manager.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Each release is given its own *-updates* repository (e.g. intrepid-updates).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The repository is supported by Canonical Ltd. for packages in main and restricted, and by the community for packages in universe and multiverse.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] All updates to the repository must meet certain requirements and go through the *-proposed* repository before being made available to the public.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In addition to the *-updates* repository, the unstable *-proposed* repository contains uploads that must be confirmed before being copied into *-updates*.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] All updates must go through this process to ensure that the patch does truly fix the bug and there is no risk of regression.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Canonical previously hosted a partner repository that let vendors of proprietary software deliver their products to Ubuntu users at no cost through the same familiar tools for installing and upgrading software.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The software in the partner repository was officially supported with security and other important updates by its respective vendors.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Canonical supported the packaging of the software for Ubuntu and provided guidance to vendors.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] However, in anticipation for the release of Ubuntu 22.04 LTS Canonical closed the partner repository, as the only package still hosted in it was Adobe Flash, which would not be released with 22.04.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu developer Steve Langasek said in a development mailing list that he felt the "Snap Store has matured to the point that I believe it supersedes the partner archive".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] A *Personal Package Archive* (PPA) is a software repository for uploading source packages to be built and published as an Advanced Packaging Tool (APT) repository by Canonical's Launchpad service.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] While the term is used exclusively within Ubuntu, Canonical, envisions adoption beyond the Ubuntu community.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Some third-party software that does not limit distribution is included in Ubuntu's multiverse component.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The package *ubuntu-restricted-extras* additionally contains software that may be legally restricted, including support for DVD playback, Microsoft TrueType core fonts, many common audio/video codecs, and unrar, an unarchiver for files compressed in the RAR file format.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Additionally, third-party application suites are available for download via Ubuntu Software and the Snap store, including many games such as Braid, Minecraft and Oil Rush, software for DVD playback and media codecs.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu follows a time-based release cycle, issuing new versions every six months.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Each standard release receives nine months of free support, including security updates and high-impact bug fixes.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Every fourth release, occurring in the second quarter of even-numbered years, is designated a long-term support (LTS) release.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] LTS releases receive five years of free support, with the option to extend support up to ten years through the Expanded Security Maintenance (ESM) program, available through the Ubuntu Pro subscriptions, which are free for personal use.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu version numbers reflect the year and month of release.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For example, Ubuntu 4.10 was released in October 2004.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Each release also has an alliterative code name, typically consisting of an adjective and an animal (e.g., "Bionic Beaver").
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Releases are often referred to by the adjective alone.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu releases are typically scheduled about one month after corresponding GNOME releases.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu Desktop (formally named as Ubuntu Desktop Edition, and simply called Ubuntu) is the variant officially recommended for most users.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] It is designed for desktop and laptop PCs and is officially supported by Canonical.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Variants are distinguished simply by each featuring a different desktop environment, or, in the case of Ubuntu Server, no desktop.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] LXQt and Xfce are often recommended for use with older PCs that may have less memory and processing power available.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Most Ubuntu editions and flavours simply install a different set of default packages compared to the standard Ubuntu Desktop.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Since they share the same package repositories, all of the same software is available for each of them.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu Core is the sole exception as it only has access to packages in the Snap Store.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu had some official distributions that have been discontinued, such as Gobuntu; including some previously supported by Canonical, like Ubuntu Touch, that is now maintained by volunteers (UBports Community).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Alongside the official flavours are those that are unofficial.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] These are still in the process of becoming recognised as official flavours by Canonical.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu offers Ubuntu Cloud Images which are pre-installed disk images that have been customised by Ubuntu engineering to run on cloud-platforms such as Amazon EC2, OpenStack, Microsoft Azure and LXC.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu is also prevalent on VPS platforms such as DigitalOcean.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu has support for OpenStack, with Eucalyptus to OpenStack migration tools added by Canonical.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu 11.10 added focus on OpenStack as the Ubuntu's preferred IaaS offering, though Eucalyptus is also supported.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Another major focus is Canonical Juju for provisioning, deploying, hosting, managing, and orchestrating enterprise data centre infrastructure services, by, with, and for the Ubuntu Server.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu was awarded the Reader Award for best Linux distribution at the 2005 LinuxWorld Conference and Expo in London, received favourable reviews in online and print publications, and has won InfoWorld's 2007 Bossie Award for *Best Open Source Client OS*.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In early 2008, *PC World* named Ubuntu the "best all-around Linux distribution available today", though it criticized the lack of an integrated desktop effects manager.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Chris DiBona, the program manager for open-source software at Google, said "I think Ubuntu has captured people's imaginations around the Linux desktop," and "If there is a hope for the Linux desktop, it would be them".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As of January 2009, almost half of Google's 20,000 employees used Goobuntu, a slightly modified version of Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2012, *ZDNet* reported that Ubuntu was still Google's desktop of choice.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In March 2016, Matt Hartley picked a list of best Linux distributions for *Datamation*; he chose Ubuntu as number one.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2008, Jamie Hyneman, co-host of the American television series *MythBusters*, advocated Linux (giving the example of Ubuntu) as a solution to software bloat.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Other celebrity users of Ubuntu include science fiction writer Cory Doctorow and actor Stephen Fry.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In January 2014, the UK's authority for computer security, CESG, reported that Ubuntu 12.04 LTS was "the only operating system that passes as many as 9 out of 12 requirements without any significant risks", though it was unclear if any other Linux distributions were tested.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As Ubuntu is distributed freely and historically, there was no registration process (still optional), Ubuntu usage can only be roughly estimated.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2015, Canonical's Ubuntu Insights page stated, "Ubuntu now has over 40 million desktop users and counting".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] W3Techs analyses the top 10 million websites only.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Wikimedia Foundation data (based on user agent) for September 2013 shows that Ubuntu generated the most page requests to Wikimedia sites, including Wikipedia, among recognizable Linux distributions.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Other supercomputers running Ubuntu also rank high on the list e.g.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] NVIDIA's Selene supercomputer still ranks highly, and was fifth-fastest one in the world in November 2022 after an upgrade from seventh place, where it entered the list in June.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Another Nvidia-based supercomputer using Ubuntu previously topped the Green500 list (it and the next one was also Ubuntu-based), a list which is a reordering of former list, ordered by power-efficiency.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] On the TOP500 list, that supercomputer was ranked 170nd (and many Ubuntu-based rank higher than that).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The public sector has also adopted Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As of January 2009, the Ministry of Education and Science of North Macedonia deployed more than 180,000 Ubuntu-based classroom desktops, and has encouraged every student in the country to use Ubuntu-powered computer workstations; the Spanish school system has 195,000 Ubuntu desktops.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The French police, having already started using open-source software in 2005 by replacing Microsoft Office with OpenOffice.org, decided to transition to Ubuntu from Windows XP after the release of Windows Vista in 2006.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] By March 2009, the Gendarmerie Nationale had already switched 5,000 workstations to Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Based on the success of that transition, it planned to switch 15,000 more over by the end of 2009 and to have switched all 90,000 workstations over by 2015 (GendBuntu project).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Colonel Guimard announced that the move was very easy and allowed for a 70% saving on the IT budget without having to reduce its capabilities.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2011, Ubuntu 10.04 was adopted by the Indian justice system.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2004, the city of Munich, Germany, started the LiMux project, and later forked Kubuntu 10.04 LTS for use on the city's computers.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] After originally planning to migrate 12,000 desktop computers to LiMux, it was announced in December 2013 that the project had completed successfully with the migration of 14,800 out of 15,500 desktop computers, but still keeping about 5,000 Windows clients for unported applications.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In February 2017 the majority coalition decided, against heavy protest from the opposition, to evaluate the migration back to Windows, after Microsoft had decided to move its company headquarters to Munich.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In May 2020, the recently elected Alliance 90/The Greens party and the Social Democrat party negotiated a new coalition agreement, stating: "Where it is technologically and financially possible, the city will emphasize open standards and free open-source licensed software".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In March 2012, the government of Iceland launched a project to get all public institutions using free and open-source software.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Already, several government agencies and schools have adopted Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The government cited cost savings as a big factor for the decision, and also stated that open-source software avoids vendor lock-in.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] A 12-month project was launched to migrate the biggest public institutions in Iceland to using open-source software, and help ease the migration for others.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] US president Barack Obama's successful campaign for re-election in 2012 used Ubuntu in its IT department.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In August 2014, the city of Turin, Italy, announced its migration from Windows XP to Ubuntu for the 8,300 desktop computers used by the municipality, becoming the first city in Italy to adopt Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Starting in 2008, the Wikimedia Foundation, the non-profit organization behind Wikipedia, switched from multiple different Linux operating systems to Ubuntu (in 2019, it switched again, from Ubuntu to Debian).
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] During the 2010s, some Tesla Model S owners, discovered via little hack that the touchscreen computer for entertainment and navigation assistance, runs on an adapted version of Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In June 2019, Canonical announced that they would be deprecating support for 32-bit applications and libraries in Ubuntu 19.10.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Because Steam's Linux client depends on these 32-bit libraries, Valve announced that they would no longer be supporting Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] After uproar from the Linux gaming community, Canonical backtracked on this decision and decided to support select 32-bit libraries.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As a result, Valve decided that Steam would support Ubuntu 19.10 again.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Wine needs most of the same 32-bit library packages that the Steam package depends on, and more, to enable its version of WoW64 to run 32-bit Windows applications.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] The parts of Wine that would continue to function without 32-bit libraries would be limited to the subset of Windows applications that have a 64-bit version, removing decades of Windows compatibility.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In Canonical's statement on bringing back the libraries, they mentioned using "container technology" in the future to make sure that Wine continues to function.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Soon after being introduced in 2012, doubts emerged on the conformance of the *shopping lens* (a feature that displays Amazon suggestions in the searching tool Unity Dash) with the European Data Protection Directive.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] A petition was later signed and delivered to Canonical demanding various modifications to the feature to clearly frame it within European law.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2013, a formal complaint on the shopping lens was filed with the Information Commissioner's Office (ICO), the UK data privacy office.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Almost one year later, the ICO ruled in favour of Canonical, considering the various improvements introduced to the feature conformed with the Data Protection Directive.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] According to European rules, this ruling is automatically effective in the entirety of the European Union.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] However, the ruling also made clear that at the time of introduction the feature was not legal, among other things, since it was missing a privacy policy statement.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu has integrated increasing quantities of advertising into the operating system's terminal, leading to multiple controversies with its user base.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2017, Canonical placed a message regarding HBO's Silicon Valley in the MOTD file, causing the message to be shown whenever a terminal session started.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Over the following years, more messages would be placed into the MOTD.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2022, ads for Ubuntu's premium service, Ubuntu Advantage, were introduced into the apt system update utility.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] This move caused controversy in the user community, with some users considering advertising a fair business model to support development, while other users found the inclusion inappropriate and annoying.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] To reach out to users who are less technical, and to foster a sense of community around the distribution, Local Communities, better known as "LoCos", have been established throughout the world.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Originally, each country had one LoCo Team.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] However, in some areas, most notably the United States and Canada, each state or province may establish a team.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] A LoCo Council approves teams based upon their efforts to aid in either the development or the promotion of Ubuntu.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu has received broad support from hardware vendors, with several manufacturers offering computers pre-installed with the operating system.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Canonical collaborates with original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) to certify and support Ubuntu on a variety of devices, primarily targeting enterprise and developer markets.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Major OEMs such as Dell, Lenovo, and HP have offered laptops and desktops with Ubuntu as an alternative to Windows, often through online configuration options or regional sales channels.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Ubuntu is also offered on the IBM Z series of mainframes.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Smaller vendors such as System76 and OnLogic also ship systems with Ubuntu pre-installed, sometimes offering firmware customization or support options through Canonical.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Many Windows applications can be run on Ubuntu, much like in other Linux distributions, using the Wine compatibility layer, which can be managed via frontends such as Bottles.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Steam has a Windows compatibility layer called Proton, and it has derivatives such as GE-Proton.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Multiple Windows virtual machines can also be installed by KVM/QEMU and Virt-Manager.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Graphics settings are easiest in QXL/SPICE mode.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] For 3D accelerated graphics performance, there is a third-party VirGL driver or GPU Full Passthrough mode.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In a networked environment, file sharing between Ubuntu Linux and Windows is possible by Samba client/server software.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Host Ubuntu Linux and the guest Windows virtual machines are also virtually networked in KVM, so file sharing between the host and virtual guest machines can also be done by the Samba in the KVM environment.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] RDP server of GNOME Remote Desktop and Remmina client software is used for remote desktop connection between Ubuntu Linux and the other OSs.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In March 2016, Microsoft announced that it would support the Ubuntu userland on top of the Windows 10 kernel by implementing the Linux system calls as a subsystem.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] At the time, it was focused on command-line tools like Bash and was aimed at software developers.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] WSL was made available with Windows 10, version 1709.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] As of 2019, other Linux distributions are also supported.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2019, Microsoft announced the new WSL 2 subsystem that includes a Linux kernel, that Canonical announced will have "full support for Ubuntu".
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] By this time, it was possible to run graphical Linux apps on Windows.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In 2021, Microsoft went on to add out-of-the-box support for graphical Linux apps, through the WSLg project.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] In May 2021, Microsoft extended its Threat and Vulnerability Management solution, which was a Windows-only solution thus far, to support Ubuntu, RHEL, and CentOS.
[src:snap-packages/ubuntu] Starting with version 6, PowerShell runs on Ubuntu and can manage both Windows and Ubuntu computers remotely from either platforms.
